arch:property.oc:show_val: Flot smpl #2 (5642), > 4mm, diagnostics only. This is a medium-size, rich unit with many large fragments of sheep and goat bone. There are 3 X-finds including a domestic goat horn, a bone point and a sheep foot - however, the bone point seems to have gone somewhere else. The unit is mixed in colour from white to moderately weathered, but is generally a light brown colour. There is about 3% burning mainly carbonized long bone fragments. There is little digestion or trample polish. Body parts are overwhelmingly sheep-goat head and feet with both adult and infantile individuals. The infantile bones are solid and surprisingly common - there are both infantile caprids and infantile cattle. There are a few fore limb fragments, scapula fragments and a small amount of vert and ribs. There are almost no pelvis or hind limb parts. The general impression is post-butchery waste with a little mixed garbage thrown in. The preservation of the infantile bones is excellent suggesting that the unit was quickly buried and well preserved. It is possible there is a bit of mixing from a nearby late pit. The mix is more kitchen garbage then specialized deposit although the high number of infantile bones is unusual. Taxa include sheep, domestic goat, large (possibly wild) goat and two cattle bone including one infantile one. The complete sheep foot was found in association with a pot stand, a pot boiler and a broken pot(?). The foot was given the X number X6. i have given this number to one of the first phalanx and the rest have F numbers. One bird bone was pulled for export. The flot sample has a very little of the very white bone. It is mainly medium brown fragments under 1 cm. There are a few large pieces including a human tarsal and a cattle third phalange, but the mean fragment size is small with the overwhelming majority of pieces under 1 cm. The fragments are mixed, but not rolled or trampled. Most are long bone, rib or vertebra fragments. 2 fish bones were pulled from the flot for further study. NR 2007: For some reason, a worked bone specimen, a bead (?) that looks like a cufflink, made it to the lab this year from the >4mm flotation, unknown sample number, flot 5642.

arch:string.div: The unique identifier for each contextual unit, matching those used in the central Çatalhöyük excavation database and in publications. The excavation uses single-context recording.
